In JavaScript template literals, using the backticks (`) allows you to include line breaks directly in the string by pressing Enter. However, HTML rendering line breaks with `<br>` tags might not work as expected within template literals.

To display a line break in HTML content, you can use the actual HTML line break tag `<br>`, but you should set the `innerHTML` of an element to render it correctly.

Here is an example of how you can modify your code to display line breaks correctly:

```javascript
const message = `Congratulations you have built your first train line. Your construction costs were £50,000. You have £50,000 remaining.
You now need to buy a train`;

// Create an element to hold the message
const messageDiv = document.createElement('div');
messageDiv.innerHTML = message;

// Add the message to the document body or any other element
document.body.appendChild(messageDiv);
```

By setting the `innerHTML` property of an HTML element and inserting the template literal containing line breaks, the message will be displayed with the line breaks rendered as `<br>` tags.

To display the line breaks as intended in HTML, you can create a text node object to hold the message and then append it to an HTML element using the `appendChild()` method. Here's how you can adapt the code to display the message with line breaks correctly:

```javascript
const message = `Congratulations you have built your first train line. Your construction costs were £50,000. You have £50,000 remaining.\nYou now need to buy a train`;

// Create a text node with the message
const textNode = document.createTextNode(message);

// Create a <div> element to hold the text node
const messageDiv = document.createElement('div');
messageDiv.appendChild(textNode);

// Add the message to the document body or any other element
document.body.appendChild(messageDiv);
```

By creating a text node for the message and appending it to a `<div>` element, you can ensure that the line breaks (`\n` in the template literal) are displayed correctly in the HTML content.

